# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: zero-trust-network-access
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] It was created in response to the 2009 Operation Aurora.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] An open source implementation inspired by Google's research paper on an access proxy is known as "transcend".
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] Google documented its Zero Trust journey from 2014 to 2018 through a series of articles in the journal ;login:.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] Google called their ZT network "BeyondCorp".
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] Google implemented a Zero Trust architecture on a large scale, and relied on user and device credentials, regardless of location.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] Data was encrypted and protected from managed devices.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] Unmanaged devices, such as BYOD, were not given access to the BeyondCorp resources.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] BeyondCorp utilized a zero trust security model, which is a relatively new security model that it assumes that all devices and users are potentially compromised.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] This is in contrast to traditional security models, which rely on firewalls and other perimeter defenses to protect sensitive data.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] The corporate network grants no inherent trust, and all internal apps are accessed via the BeyondCorp system, regardless of whether the user is in a Google office or working remotely.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] BeyondCorp is related to Zero Trust architecture as it implements a true Zero Trust network, where all access is granted on identity, device, and authentication, based on robust underlying device and identity data sources.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] BeyondCorp works by using a number of security policies including authentication, authorization, and access control to ensure that only authorized users can access corporate resources.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] Authentication verifies the identity of the user, authorization determines whether the user has permission to access the requested resource, and access control policies restrict what the user can do with the resource.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] One of the main components in BeyondCorp's implementation is the Trust Inferrer.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] The Trust Inferrer is a security component (typically software) that looks at information about a user's device, like a computer or phone, to decide how much it can be trusted to access certain resources like important company documents.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] The Trust Inferrer checks things like the security of the device, whether it has the right software installed, and if it belongs to an authorized user.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] Based on all this information, the Trust Inferrer decides what the device can access and what it can't.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] Unlike traditional VPNs, BeyondCorp's access policies are based on information about a device, its state, and its associated user.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] BeyondCorp considers both internal networks and external networks to be completely untrusted, and gates access to applications by dynamically asserting and enforcing levels, or “tiers,” of access.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] BeyondCorp utilized a Device Inventory Database and Device Identity that uniquely identifies a device through a digital certificate.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] Any changes to the device are recorded in the Device Inventory Database.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] The certificate is used to uniquely identify a device; however, additional information is required to grant access privileges to a resource.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] Another important component of BeyondCorp's implementation is the Access Control Engine.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] Think of this as the brain of the Zero Trust architecture.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] The Access Control Engine is like a traffic cop standing at an intersection.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] Its job is to make sure that only authorized devices and users are allowed to access specific resources (like files or applications) on the network.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] It checks the access policy (the rules that say who can access what), the device's state (like whether it has the right software updates or security settings), and the resources being requested.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] Then it makes a decision on whether to grant or deny access based on all of this information.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] It helps ensure that only the right people and devices are allowed access to the network, which helps keep things secure.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] The Access Control Engine utilizes the output from the Trust Inferrer and other data that is fed into its system.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] One of the first things Google did to implement a Zero Trust architecture was to capture and analyze network traffic.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] The purpose of analyzing the traffic was to build a baseline of what typical network traffic looked like.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] In doing so, BeyondCorp also discovered unusual, unexpected, and unauthorized traffic.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/beyondcorp] This was very useful because it gave the BeyondCorp engineers critical information that assisted them in reengineering the system in a secure manner.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] For example, in IEEE 802.11 (Wi-Fi) the WPA and WPA2 standards have adopted IEEE 802.1X (with various EAP types) as the canonical authentication mechanism.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP is an authentication framework, not a specific authentication mechanism.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] It provides some common functions and negotiation of authentication methods called EAP methods.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] There are currently about 40 different methods defined.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Methods defined in IETF RFCs include EAP-MD5, EAP-POTP, EAP-GTC, EAP-TLS, EAP-IKEv2, EAP-SIM, EAP-AKA, and EAP-AKA'.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Additionally, a number of vendor-specific methods and new proposals exist.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Commonly used modern methods capable of operating in wireless networks include EAP-TLS, EAP-SIM, EAP-AKA, LEAP and EAP-TTLS.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Requirements for EAP methods used in wireless LAN authentication are described in RFC 4017.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The list of type and packets codes used in EAP is available from the IANA EAP Registry.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The standard also describes the conditions under which the AAA key management requirements described in RFC 4962 can be satisfied.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The Lightweight Extensible Authentication Protocol (LEAP) method was developed by Cisco Systems prior to the IEEE ratification of the 802.11i security standard.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco distributed the protocol through the CCX (Cisco Certified Extensions) as part of getting 802.1X and dynamic WEP adoption into the industry in the absence of a standard.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] There is no native support for LEAP in any Windows operating system, but it is widely supported by third-party client software most commonly included with WLAN (wireless LAN) devices.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] LEAP support for Microsoft Windows 7 and Microsoft Windows Vista can be added by downloading a client add in from Cisco that provides support for both LEAP and EAP-FAST.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Due to the wide adoption of LEAP in the networking industry many other WLAN vendors claim support for LEAP.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] LEAP uses a modified version of MS-CHAP, an authentication protocol in which user credentials are not strongly protected and easily compromised; an exploit tool called ASLEAP was released in early 2004 by Joshua Wright.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco recommends that customers who absolutely must use LEAP do so only with sufficiently complex passwords, though complex passwords are difficult to administer and enforce.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco's current recommendation is to use newer and stronger EAP protocols such as EAP-FAST, PEAP, or EAP-TLS.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Transport Layer Security (EAP-TLS), defined in RFC 5216, is an IETF open standard that uses the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol, and is well-supported among wireless vendors.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TLS is the original, standard wireless LAN EAP authentication protocol.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TLS is still considered one of the most secure EAP standards available, although TLS provides strong security only as long as the user understands potential warnings about false credentials, and is universally supported by all manufacturers of wireless LAN hardware and software.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Until April 2005, EAP-TLS was the only EAP type vendors needed to certify for a WPA or WPA2 logo.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] There are client and server implementations of EAP-TLS in 3Com, Apple, Avaya, Brocade Communications, Cisco, Enterasys Networks, Fortinet, Foundry, Hirschmann, HP, Juniper, Microsoft, and open source operating systems.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TLS is natively supported in Mac OS X 10.3 and above, wpa_supplicant, Windows 2000 SP4, Windows XP and above, Windows Mobile 2003 and above, Windows CE 4.2, and Apple's iOS mobile operating system.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Unlike most TLS implementations of HTTPS, such as on the World Wide Web, the majority of implementations of EAP-TLS require mutual authentication using client-side X.509 certificates without giving the option to disable the requirement, even though the standard does not mandate their use.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Some have identified this as having the potential to dramatically reduce adoption of EAP-TLS and prevent "open" but encrypted access points.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] This would allow for situations much like HTTPS, where a wireless hotspot allows free access and does not authenticate station clients but station clients wish to use encryption (IEEE 802.11i-2004 i.e.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] WPA2) and potentially authenticate the wireless hotspot.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] There have also been proposals to use IEEE 802.11u for access points to signal that they allow EAP-TLS using only server-side authentication, using the standard EAP-TLS IETF type instead of a vendor-specific EAP type.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The requirement for a client-side certificate, however unpopular it may be, is what gives EAP-TLS its authentication strength and illustrates the classic convenience vs. security trade-off.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] With a client-side certificate, a compromised password is not enough to break into EAP-TLS enabled systems because the intruder still needs to have the client-side certificate; indeed, a password is not even needed, as it is only used to encrypt the client-side certificate for storage.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The highest security available is when the "private keys" of client-side certificate are housed in smart cards.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] This is because there is no way to steal a client-side certificate's corresponding private key from a smart card without stealing the card itself.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is more likely that the physical theft of a smart card would be noticed (and the smart card immediately revoked) than a (typical) password theft would be noticed.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] In addition, the private key on a smart card is typically encrypted using a PIN that only the owner of the smart card knows, minimizing its utility for a thief even before the card has been reported stolen and revoked.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-MD5 was the only IETF Standards Track based EAP method when it was first defined in the original RFC for EAP, RFC 2284.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] It offers minimal security; the MD5 hash function is vulnerable to dictionary attacks, and does not support key generation, which makes it unsuitable for use with dynamic WEP, or WPA/WPA2 enterprise.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-MD5 differs from other EAP methods in that it only provides authentication of the EAP peer to the EAP server but not mutual authentication.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] By not providing EAP server authentication, this EAP method is vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-MD5 support was first included in Windows 2000 and deprecated in Windows Vista.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Protected One-Time Password (EAP-POTP), which is described in RFC 4793, is an EAP method developed by RSA Laboratories that uses one-time password (OTP) tokens, such as a handheld hardware device or a hardware or software module running on a personal computer, to generate authentication keys.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-POTP can be used to provide unilateral or mutual authentication and key material in protocols that use EAP.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP-POTP method provides two-factor user authentication, meaning that a user needs both physical access to a token and knowledge of a personal identification number (PIN) to perform authentication.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Pre-shared key (EAP-PSK), defined in RFC 4764, is an EAP method for mutual authentication and session key derivation using a pre-shared key (PSK).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] It provides a protected communication channel, when mutual authentication is successful, for both parties to communicate and is designed for authentication over insecure networks such as IEEE 802.11.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-PSK is documented in an experimental RFC that provides a lightweight and extensible EAP method that does not require any public-key cryptography.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP method protocol exchange is done in a minimum of four messages.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Password (EAP-PWD), defined in RFC 5931, is an EAP method which uses a shared password for authentication.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The password may be a low-entropy one and may be drawn from some set of possible passwords, like a dictionary, which is available to an attacker.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The underlying key exchange is resistant to active attack, passive attack, and dictionary attack.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-PWD is in the base of Android 4.0 (ICS).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is in FreeRADIUS and Radiator RADIUS servers, and it is in hostapd and wpa_supplicant.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Tunneled Transport Layer Security (EAP-TTLS) is an EAP protocol that extends TLS.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] It was co-developed by Funk Software and Certicom and is widely supported across platforms.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Microsoft did not incorporate native support for the EAP-TTLS protocol in Windows XP, Vista, or 7.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Supporting TTLS on these platforms requires third-party Encryption Control Protocol (ECP) certified software.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Microsoft Windows started EAP-TTLS support with Windows 8, support for EAP-TTLS appeared in Windows Phone version 8.1.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The client can, but does not have to be authenticated via a CA-signed PKI certificate to the server.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] This greatly simplifies the setup procedure since a certificate is not needed on every client.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] After the server is securely authenticated to the client via its CA certificate and optionally the client to the server, the server can then use the established secure connection ("tunnel") to authenticate the client.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] It can use an existing and widely deployed authentication protocol and infrastructure, incorporating legacy password mechanisms and authentication databases, while the secure tunnel provides protection from eavesdropping and man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Note that the user's name is never transmitted in unencrypted clear text, improving privacy.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Two distinct versions of EAP-TTLS exist: original EAP-TTLS (a.k.a.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-TTLSv0 is described in RFC 5281, EAP-TTLSv1 is available as an Internet draft.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] 2 (EAP-IKEv2) is an EAP method based on the Internet Key Exchange protocol version 2 (IKEv2).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] It provides mutual authentication and session key establishment between an EAP peer and an EAP server.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] bit strings that are known to both the server and the peer.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] High-entropy bit strings that are known to both the server and the peer.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is possible to use a different authentication credential (and thereby technique) in each direction.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] For example, the EAP server authenticates itself using public/private key pair and the EAP peer using symmetric key.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] However, not all of the nine theoretical combinations are expected in practice.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Specifically, the standard RFC 5106 lists four use cases: The server authenticating with an asymmetric key pair while the client uses any of the three methods; and that both sides use a symmetric key.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-IKEv2 is described in RFC 5106, and a prototype implementation exists.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Flexible Authentication via Secure Tunneling (EAP-FAST; RFC 4851) is a protocol proposal by Cisco Systems as a replacement for LEAP.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The protocol was designed to address the weaknesses of LEAP while preserving the "lightweight" implementation.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Use of server certificates is optional in EAP-FAST.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-FAST uses a Protected Access Credential (PAC) to establish a TLS tunnel in which client credentials are verified.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] When automatic PAC provisioning is enabled, EAP-FAST has a vulnerability where an attacker can intercept the PAC and use that to compromise user credentials.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] This vulnerability is mitigated by manual PAC provisioning or by using server certificates for the PAC provisioning phase.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is worth noting that the PAC file is issued on a per-user basis.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] This is a requirement in RFC 4851 sec 7.4.4 so if a new user logs on the network from a device, a new PAC file must be provisioned first.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] This is one reason why it is difficult not to run EAP-FAST in insecure anonymous provisioning mode.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The alternative is to use device passwords instead, but then the device is validated on the network not the user.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-FAST can be used without PAC files, falling back to normal TLS.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-FAST is natively supported in Apple OS X 10.4.8 and newer.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Cisco supplies an EAP-FAST module for Windows Vista and later operating systems which have an extensible EAPHost architecture for new authentication methods and supplicants.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Tunnel Extensible Authentication Protocol (TEAP; RFC 7170) is a tunnel-based EAP method that enables secure communication between a peer and a server by using the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol to establish a mutually authenticated tunnel.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Within the tunnel, TLV (Type-Length-Value) objects are used to convey authentication-related data between the EAP peer and the EAP server.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] In addition to peer authentication, TEAP allows the peer to ask the server for a certificate by sending a request in PKCS#10 format.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] After receiving the certificate request and authenticating the peer, the server can provision a certificate to the peer in PKCS#7 format (RFC 2325).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The server can also distribute trusted root certificates to the peer in PKCS#7 format (RFC 2325).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Both operations are enclosed into the corresponding TLVs and happen securely within the already established TLS tunnel.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Subscriber Identity Module (EAP-SIM) is used for authentication and session key distribution using the subscriber identity module (SIM) from the Global System for Mobile Communications (GSM).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] GSM cellular networks use a subscriber identity module card to carry out user authentication.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-SIM uses a SIM authentication algorithm between the client and an Authentication, Authorization and Accounting (AAA) server providing mutual authentication between the client and the network.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] In EAP-SIM the communication between the SIM card and the Authentication Centre (AuC) replaces the need for a pre-established password between the client and the AAA server.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The A3/A8 algorithms are being run a few times, with different 128 bit challenges, so there will be more 64 bit Kc-s which will be combined/mixed to create stronger keys (Kc-s won't be used directly).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The lack of mutual authentication in GSM has also been overcome.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Extensible Authentication Protocol Method for Universal Mobile Telecommunications System (UMTS) Authentication and Key Agreement (EAP-AKA), is an EAP mechanism for authentication and session key distribution using the UMTS Subscriber Identity Module (USIM).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP-AKA' variant of EAP-AKA, defined in RFC 5448, and is used for non-3GPP access to a 3GPP core network.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP Generic Token Card, or EAP-GTC, is an EAP method created by Cisco as an alternative to PEAPv0/EAP-MSCHAPv2 and defined in RFC 2284 and RFC 3748.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-GTC carries a text challenge from the authentication server, and a reply generated by a security token.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The PEAP-GTC authentication mechanism allows generic authentication to a number of databases such as Novell Directory Service (NDS) and Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP), as well as the use of a one-time password.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP with the encrypted key exchange, or EAP-EKE, is one of the few EAP methods that provide secure mutual authentication using short passwords and no need for public key certificates.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is a three-round exchange, based on the Diffie-Hellman variant of the well-known EKE protocol.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Nimble out-of-band authentication for EAP (EAP-NOOB) is a generic bootstrapping solution for devices which have no pre-configured authentication credentials and which are not yet registered on any server.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] It is especially useful for Internet-of-Things (IoT) gadgets and toys that come with no information about any owner, network or server.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Authentication for this EAP method is based on a user-assisted out-of-band (OOB) channel between the server and peer.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-NOOB supports many types of OOB channels such as QR codes, NFC tags, audio etc. and unlike other EAP methods, the protocol security has been verified by formal modeling of the specification with ProVerif and MCRL2 tools.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP-NOOB performs an Ephemeral Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellman (ECDHE) over the in-band EAP channel.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The user then confirms this exchange by transferring the OOB message.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Users can transfer the OOB message from the peer to the server, when for example, the device is a smart TV that can show a QR code.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Alternatively, users can transfer the OOB message from the server to the peer, when for example, the device being bootstrapped is a camera that can only read a QR code.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP is not a wire protocol; instead it only defines message formats.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Each protocol that uses EAP defines a way to encapsulate EAP messages within that protocol's messages.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The encapsulation of EAP over IEEE 802 is defined in IEEE 802.1X and known as "EAP over LANs" or EAPOL.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAPOL was originally designed for IEEE 802.3 Ethernet in 802.1X-2001, but was clarified to suit other IEEE 802 LAN technologies such as IEEE 802.11 wireless and Fiber Distributed Data Interface (ANSI X3T9.5/X3T12, adopted as ISO 9314) in 802.1X-2004.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAPOL protocol was also modified for use with IEEE 802.1AE (MACsec) and IEEE 802.1AR (Initial Device Identity, IDevID) in 802.1X-2010.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The Protected Extensible Authentication Protocol, also known as Protected EAP or simply PEAP, is a protocol that encapsulates EAP within a potentially encrypted and authenticated Transport Layer Security (TLS) tunnel.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The purpose was to correct deficiencies in EAP; EAP assumed a protected communication channel, such as that provided by physical security, so facilities for protection of the EAP conversation were not provided.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAP was jointly developed by Cisco Systems, Microsoft, and RSA Security.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAPv0 was the version included with Microsoft Windows XP and was nominally defined in draft-kamath-pppext-peapv0-00.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAPv1 and PEAPv2 were defined in different versions of *draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap*.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] PEAPv1 was defined in draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap-00 through draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap-05, and PEAPv2 was defined in versions beginning with draft-josefsson-pppext-eap-tls-eap-06.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The protocol only specifies chaining multiple EAP mechanisms and not any specific method.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Use of the EAP-MSCHAPv2 and EAP-GTC methods are the most commonly supported.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] Both the RADIUS and Diameter AAA protocols can encapsulate EAP messages.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] They are often used by Network Access Server (NAS) devices to forward EAP packets between IEEE 802.1X endpoints and AAA servers to facilitate IEEE 802.1X.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The Protocol for Carrying Authentication for Network Access (PANA) is an IP-based protocol that allows a device to authenticate itself with a network to be granted access.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] PANA will not define any new authentication protocol, key distribution, key agreement or key derivation protocols; for these purposes, EAP will be used, and PANA will carry the EAP payload.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] PANA allows dynamic service provider selection, supports various authentication methods, is suitable for roaming users, and is independent from the link layer mechanisms.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] EAP was originally an authentication extension for the Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] PPP has supported EAP since EAP was created as an alternative to the Challenge-Handshake Authentication Protocol (CHAP) and the Password Authentication Protocol (PAP), which were eventually incorporated into EAP.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/extensible-authentication-protocol] The EAP extension to PPP was first defined in RFC 2284, now obsoleted by RFC 3748.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/network-segmentation] When a cyber-criminal gains unauthorized access to a network, segmentation or “zoning” can provide effective controls to limit further movement across the network.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/network-segmentation] For example separating the network for Payment Card authorizations from those for Point-of-Service (till) or customer Wi-Fi traffic.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/network-segmentation] A sound security policy entails segmenting the network into multiple zones, with varying security requirements, and rigorously enforcing the policy on what is allowed to move from zone to zone.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/network-segmentation] Finance and Human Resources typically need access via their own VLAN to their application servers because of the confidential nature of the information they process and store.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/network-segmentation] Other groups of personnel may require their own segregated networks, such as server administrators, security administration, managers and executives.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/network-segmentation] Third parties are usually required to have their own segments, with different administration passwords to the main network, to avoid attacks via a compromised, less well protected, third party site.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/network-segmentation] Segregation is typically achieved by a combination of firewalls and VLANs (virtual local area networks).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/network-segmentation] Software-defined networking (SDN) can allow the creation and management of micro-segmented networks.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle means giving any user accounts or processes only those privileges which are essentially vital to perform its intended functions.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, a user account for the sole purpose of creating backups does not need to install software: hence, it has rights only to run backup and backup-related applications.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] Any other privileges, such as installing new software, are blocked.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle applies also to a personal computer user who usually does work in a normal user account, and opens a privileged, password protected account only when the situation absolutely demands it.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] When applied to users, the terms *least user access* or *least-privileged user account* (LUA) are also used, referring to the concept that all user accounts should run with as few privileges as possible, and also launch applications with as few privileges as possible.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle (of least privilege) is widely recognized as an important design consideration towards enhancing and giving a much needed 'Boost' to the protection of data and functionality from faults (fault tolerance) and malicious behavior.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, there exist multiple competing definitions of true (least privilege).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] As program complexity increases rapidly, so do the number of potential issues, rendering a predictive approach impractical.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] Examples include the values of variables it may process, addresses it will need, or the precise time such things will be required.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] Object capability systems allow, for instance, deferring granting a single-use privilege until the time when it will be used.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] Currently, the closest practical approach is to eliminate privileges that can be manually evaluated as unnecessary.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] The resulting set of privileges typically exceeds the true minimum required privileges for the process.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] Another limitation is the granularity of control that the operating environment has over privileges for an individual process.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, it is rarely possible to control a process's access to memory, processing time, I/O device addresses or modes with the precision needed to facilitate only the precise set of privileges a process will require.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] Denning, in his paper "Fault Tolerant Operating Systems", set it in a broader perspective among "The four fundamental principles of fault tolerance".
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] "Dynamic assignments of privileges" was earlier discussed by Roger Needham in 1972.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] Historically, the oldest instance of (least privilege) is probably the source code of *login.c*, which begins execution with super-user permissions and—the instant they are no longer necessary—dismisses them via *setuid()* with a non-zero argument as demonstrated in the Version 6 Unix source code.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] The kernel always runs with maximum privileges since it is the operating system core and has hardware access.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] One of the principal responsibilities of an operating system, particularly a multi-user operating system, is management of the hardware's availability and requests to access it from running processes.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] When the kernel crashes, the mechanisms by which it maintains state also fail.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] Therefore, even if there is a way for the CPU to recover without a hard reset, security continues to be enforced, but the operating system cannot properly respond to the failure because it was not possible to detect the failure.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] This is because kernel execution either halted or the program counter resumed execution from somewhere in an endless, and—usually—non-functional loop.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] This would be akin to either experiencing amnesia (kernel execution failure) or being trapped in a closed maze that always returns to the starting point (closed loops).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] If execution picks up after the crash by loading and running trojan code, the author of the trojan code can usurp control of all processes.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle of least privilege forces code to run with the lowest privilege/permission level possible.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] This means that the code that resumes the code execution-whether trojan or simply code execution picking up from an unexpected location—would not have the ability to perform malicious or undesirable processes.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] One method used to accomplish this can be implemented in the microprocessor hardware.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, in the Intel x86 architecture the manufacturer designed four (ring 0 through ring 3) running "modes" with graduated degrees of access-much like security clearance systems in defence and intelligence agencies.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] As implemented in some operating systems, processes execute with a *potential privilege set* and an *active privilege set*.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] Such privilege sets are inherited from the parent as determined by the semantics of *fork()*.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] An executable file that performs a privileged function—thereby technically constituting a component of the TCB, and concomitantly termed a trusted program or trusted process—may also be marked with a set of privileges.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] This is a logical extension of the notions of set user ID and set group ID.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] The inheritance of file privileges by a process are determined by the semantics of the *exec()* family of system calls.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] The precise manner in which potential process privileges, actual process privileges, and file privileges interact can become complex.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, least privilege is practiced by forcing a process to run with only those privileges required by the task.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] Adherence to this model is quite complex as well as error-prone.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/principle-of-least-privilege] Least privilege has also been interpreted in the context of distribution of discretionary access control (DAC) permissions, for example asserting that giving user U read/write access to file F violates least privilege if U can complete their authorized tasks with only read permission.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] In computer networks, a **reverse proxy** or surrogate server is a proxy server that appears to any client to be an ordinary web server, but in reality merely acts as an intermediary that forwards the client's requests to one or more ordinary web servers.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies help increase scalability, performance, resilience, and security, but they also carry a number of risks.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Companies that run web servers often set up reverse proxies to facilitate the communication between an Internet user's browser and the web servers.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] An important advantage of doing so is that the web servers can be hidden behind a firewall on a company-internal network, and only the reverse proxy needs to be directly exposed to the Internet.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxy servers are implemented in popular open-source web servers.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Dedicated reverse proxy servers are used by some of the biggest websites on the Internet.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is capable of tracking IP addresses of requests that are relayed through it as well as reading and/or modifying any non-encrypted traffic.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] However, this implies that anyone who has compromised the server could do so as well.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies differ from forward proxies, which are used when the client is restricted to a private, internal network and asks a forward proxy to retrieve resources from the public Internet.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Large websites and content delivery networks use reverse proxies, together with other techniques, to balance the load between internal servers.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can keep a cache of static content, which further reduces the load on these internal servers and the internal network.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] It is also common for reverse proxies to add features such as compression or TLS encryption to the communication channel between the client and the reverse proxy.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can inspect HTTP headers, which, for example, allows them to present a single IP address to the Internet while relaying requests to different internal servers based on the URL of the HTTP request.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can hide the existence and characteristics of origin servers.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] This can make it more difficult to determine the actual location of the origin server / website and, for instance, more challenging to initiate legal action such as takedowns or block access to the website, as the IP address of the website may not be immediately apparent.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Additionally, the reverse proxy may be located in a different jurisdiction with different legal requirements, further complicating the takedown process.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Application firewall features can protect against common web-based attacks, like a denial-of-service attack (DoS) or distributed denial-of-service attacks (DDoS).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Without a reverse proxy, removing malware or initiating takedowns (while simultaneously dealing with the attack) on one's own site, for example, can be difficult.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] In the case of secure websites, a web server may not perform TLS encryption itself, but instead offload the task to a reverse proxy that may be equipped with TLS acceleration hardware.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can distribute the load from incoming requests to several servers, with each server supporting its own application area.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] In the case of reverse proxying web servers, the reverse proxy may have to rewrite the URL in each incoming request in order to match the relevant internal location of the requested resource.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can reduce load on its origin servers by caching static content and dynamic content, known as web acceleration.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Proxy caches of this sort can often satisfy a considerable number of website requests, greatly reducing the load on the origin server(s).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can optimize content by compressing it in order to speed up loading times.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] In a technique named "spoon-feeding", a dynamically generated page can be produced in its entirety and served to the reverse proxy, which can feed the page to the client as the connection allows.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] The program that generates the page need not remain open, thus releasing server resources during the possibly extended time the client requires to complete the transfer.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can operate wherever multiple web-servers must be accessible via a single public IP address.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] The web servers listen on different ports in the same machine, with the same local IP address or, possibly, on different machines with different local IP addresses.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] The reverse proxy analyzes each incoming request and delivers it to the right server within the local area network.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Reverse proxies can perform A/B testing and multivariate testing without requiring application code to handle the logic of which version is served to a client.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy can add access authentication to a web server that does not have any authentication.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] When the transit traffic is encrypted and the reverse proxy needs to filter/cache/compress or otherwise modify or improve the traffic, the proxy first must decrypt and re-encrypt communications.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] This requires the proxy to possess the TLS certificate and its corresponding private key, extending the number of systems that can have access to non-encrypted data and making it a more valuable target for attackers.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] The vast majority of external data breaches happen either when hackers succeed in abusing an existing reverse proxy that was intentionally deployed by an organization, or when hackers succeed in converting an existing Internet-facing server into a reverse proxy server.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Compromised or converted systems allow external attackers to specify where they want their attacks proxied to, enabling their access to internal networks and systems.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Applications that were developed for the internal use of a company are not typically hardened to public standards and are not necessarily designed to withstand all hacking attempts.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] When an organization allows external access to such internal applications via a reverse proxy, they might unintentionally increase their own attack surface and invite hackers.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] If a reverse proxy is not configured to filter attacks or it does not receive daily updates to keep its attack signature database up to date, a zero-day vulnerability can pass through unfiltered, enabling attackers to gain control of the system(s) that are behind the reverse proxy server.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] Giving the reverse proxy of a third party access to private keys (for caching or optimizing content) places the entire triad of confidentiality, integrity and availability in the hands of the third party who operates the proxy.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] A reverse proxy is a single point of failure for the back-end services it fronts: an outage caused by misconfiguration, a denial-of-service attack, or a software fault can make every fronted service unreachable to outside clients, even when the back-end services themselves remain healthy.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/reverse-proxy] For example, a 2020 outage at Cloudflare briefly took down major sites and services that relied on its reverse-proxy edge, including Discord.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] ZTA is implemented by establishing identity verification, validating device compliance prior to granting access, and ensuring least privilege access to only explicitly-authorized resources.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] Most modern corporate networks consist of many interconnected zones, cloud services and infrastructure, connections to remote and mobile environments, and connections to non-conventional IT, such as IoT devices.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] The traditional approach by trusting users and devices within a notional "corporate perimeter" or via a VPN connection is commonly not sufficient in the complex environment of a corporate network.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] The zero trust architecture has been proposed for use in specific areas such as supply chains.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] The principles of zero trust can be applied to data access, and to the management of data.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] This brings about zero trust data security where every request to access the data needs to be authenticated dynamically and ensure least privileged access to resources.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] In order to determine if access can be granted, policies can be applied based on the attributes of the data, who the user is, and the type of environment using Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC).
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] This zero trust data security approach can protect access to the data.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] Several definitions of zero trust have been proposed since the term was first used in 1994.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] In April 1994, the term "zero trust" was coined by Stephen Paul Marsh in his doctoral thesis on computer security at the University of Stirling.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] Marsh's work studied trust as something finite that can be described mathematically, asserting that the concept of trust transcends human factors such as morality, ethics, lawfulness, justice, and judgement.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] The problems of the Smartie or M&M model of the network (the precursor description of de-perimeterisation) was described by a Sun Microsystems engineer in a Network World article in May 1994, who described firewalls' perimeter defence, as a hard shell around a soft centre, like a Cadbury Egg.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] In 2001 the first version of the OSSTMM (Open Source Security Testing Methodology Manual) was released and this had some focus on trust.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] Version 3 which came out around 2007 has a whole chapter on Trust which says "Trust is a Vulnerability" and talks about how to apply the OSSTMM 10 controls based on Trust levels.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] In 2018, the US National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) and National Cybersecurity Center of Excellence (NCCoE) published NIST SP 800-207 – zero trust architecture.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] The publication defines zero trust as a collection of concepts and ideas designed to reduce the uncertainty in enforcing accurate, per-request access decisions in information systems and services in the face of a network viewed as compromised.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] A Zero Trust Architecture (ZTA) is an enterprise's cyber security plan that utilizes zero trust concepts and encompasses component relationships, workflow planning, and access policies.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] Therefore, a zero trust enterprise is the network infrastructure (physical and virtual) and operational policies that are in place for an enterprise as a product of a zero trust architecture plan.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] In September 2025, the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) Technical Committee CYBER (ETSI TC CYBER) published Technical Specification (TS) 104 102, which details the **ZT-Kipling methodology**.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] The ZT-Kipling methodology moves beyond the foundational principles of Zero Trust Architecture (ZTA) by defining a set of five mandatory, iterative steps.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] This methodology treats ZT as a continual and iterative process..
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] The core of the methodology’s systematic nature lies in its integration of the Kipling Criteria: what, why, when, where, who, and how.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] This entire process is repeated throughout the lifetime of a protected surface, which must be clearly defined in Step #1 of the methodology.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] TS 104 102 establishes the ZT-Kipling methodology as a systematic and cyclical governance framework for Zero Trust.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] In 2010 the term Zero Trust model was used by analyst John Kindervag of Forrester Research to denote stricter cybersecurity programs and access control within corporations.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] In 2003 the challenges of defining the perimeter to an organisation's IT systems was highlighted by the Jericho Forum, discussing the trend of what was then given the name "de-perimeterisation".
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] In response to Operation Aurora, a Chinese APT attack throughout 2009, Google started to implement a zero-trust architecture referred to as BeyondCorp an internal initiative to implement a zero trust security model that eliminated the need for a privileged VPN.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] Throughout the 2010s, zero trust architectures became more prevalent, driven in part by increased adoption of mobile and cloud services.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] In 2019 the United Kingdom National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) recommended that network architects consider a Zero Trust approach for new IT deployments, particularly where significant use of cloud services is planned.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] In the United States, Executive Order 14028 (May 2021) directed federal agencies to adopt zero trust architectures, and the Office of Management and Budget subsequently issued memorandum M-22-09 requiring agencies to meet specific zero trust security goals by the end of fiscal year 2024.
[src:zero-trust-network-access/zero-trust-security-model] In September 2025, the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) Technical Committee CYBER (ETSI TC CYBER) published Technical Specification (TS) 104 102, which details the **ZT-Kipling methodology** to be used to achieve Zero Trust security posture.
